The '''''Madonna of the Book''''', or the '''''Madonna del Libro''''', is a small painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Renaissance]] artist [[Sandro Botticelli]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/artists/sandro-botticelli|title=Sandro Botticelli|publisher=www.nationalgallery.org.uk|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://universalium.academic.ru/237120/Botticelli,_Sandro|title=Botticelli,_Sandro|publisher=/universalium.academic.ru|accessdate= November 2014}}</ref> and is preserved in the [[Museo Poldi Pezzoli|Poldi Pezzoli Museum]] in Milan. The painting is executed in [[tempera]] on panel. It dates from between 1480 and 1483.<ref name="museupoldi">{{cite web|url=http://www.museopoldipezzoli.it/en/node/631 |title=Madonna of the Book |publisher=www.museopoldipezzoli.it|accessdate=October 2014}}</ref>{{sfn|Malaguzzi|Botticelli|2004|page=40}}

==Description==
The ''Madonna of the Book'' is a soft and elegant work, in which [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]] and the [[Child Jesus|Child]] are seated by a window in the corner of a room. She holds a [[Book of Hours]], the Horae Beatae Mariae Virginis, prayer books for laymen common in the thirteenth to sixteenth centuries. The infant is gazing at his mother whilst she is absorbed in reading the book. The hands of both mother and son are positioned similarly, with the right hands open as in a gesture of blessing, and left hands closed.<ref name="museupoldi"/>

Symbolizing the [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion of Christ]], the Christ Child is holding the three [[Nail (relic)|nails]] of the [[Christian cross|cross]], and the [[crown of thorns]]. These are probably later additions, added to make the message more explicit.<ref name="milano"/><ref name="GCI"/> This is the conventional representation in the Christian [[iconography]]. In addition, the fruit in the bowl has an emblematic meaning. The [[cherry|cherries]] represent the [[blood of Christ]] or are an allusion to Paradise, [[plum]]s indicate the tenderness between Mary and the Child, and the [[Common fig|figs]] are characteristic of the Resurrection.<ref name="museupoldi"/>

Mary's blue robe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/questions/faq/faq12.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904024808/http://campus.udayton.edu/mary/questions/faq/faq12.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2006-09-04 |title=The Dayton University - The Marian Library International Marian research Institute |publisher=campus.udayton.edu |accessdate=November 2014 }}</ref> a color she is often depicted wearing, has the symbolic meanings of purity, heaven, and royalty.<ref name="madonna">{{cite web|url=http://madonnaandchild.wordpress.com/jasons-essay/|title=Madonna and Child /The artist here depicts Mary clad in her trademark blue robe. Mary is often portrayed wearing blue because blue represents purity, the virgin birth, and was often a color of royalty. /|publisher=madonnaandchild.wordpress.com|accessdate=November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://artelisaart.blogspot.se/2012/03/famous-blue-history-of-color-in-middle.html|title=The famous blue. The history-of-color|publisher=artelisaart.blogspot.se|accessdate=November 2014}}</ref>{{efn-ua|"blue as divine wisdom and contemplation, things heavenly .... joys of heavenly existence ... colors represent purity of the soul, the sins of humanity washed clean with blood of love (the sacrifice on the cross)<ref name="madonna"/>}} In this painting, as in Botticelli's other large series, the Madonna is portrayed as being serious, thoughtful and focused.<ref name="artble">{{cite web|url=http://www.artble.com/artists/sandro_botticelli|title=artists/sandro_botticelli|publisher=www.artble.com|accessdate=November 2014}}</ref>{{efn-ua|"In Botticelli's major early works (Fortitude and St. Sebastian) he changes the appearance of muscular energy and physical action as found in Verrocchio's work. The characters in Botticelli's work are displayed as melancholy and thoughtful."<ref name="artble"/>}}
<!-- A more intellectual relationship between mother and son, rather than a loving one, so unlike the works painted by [[Raphael|Raphael Sanzio]], in which often she looks at her child smiling.<ref name="museupoldi"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://totallyhistory.com/madonna-and-child-with-the-book/|title=Madonna and Child with the Book, by Raphael Sanzio|publisher=totallyhistory.com|accessdate= November 2014}}</ref> -->

Botticelli interprets the scene with a sensitivity and love for small details: the set of boxes and the [[maiolica]] bowl of lush fruits are depicted as a [[still life]]; the pages of the book, the garments, and the transparent veils exhibit a realistic tactile quality.<ref name="Gallery">{{cite web |url=http://www.wga.hu/frames-e.html?/html/b/botticel/22/2libro.html |first1=Emil |last1=Krén |first2=Daniel |last2=Marx |publisher=Web Gallery of Art |title=Madonna of the Book (Madonna del Libro) |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> The composition is refined with a good balance. Botticelli painted with subtle differences in colour, and he was able to put colours together so that they complement each other admirably. The painting is adorned with gold [[filigree]] decorating the clothes and objects. The use of gold was the result of the contractual agreement he made with the commissioner, and was included in the price of the painting.<ref name="GCI">{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/asset-viewer/the-virgin-and-child-the-madonna-of-the-book/cgHULpr5dnz9JA?hl=en#!asset-viewer:l.id=cgHULpr5dnz9JA&hl=en|title=The Virgin and Child (The Madonna of the Book)1480 |publisher=[[Google Cultural Institute]] |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref><ref name="Gallery"/>{{efn-ua|"Known also as the Madonna of the Book, this painting represents the Virgin and Child in a domestic setting, intent on reading a volume, perhaps a Book of Hours. A window is open on the landscape at twilight, but the diffused light which transforms the space into a mystical setting seems to emanate from the figures themselves.}}<ref name="museupoldi"/> Dating from about 1480, the painting shows all the elements of Botticelli's mature poetic style: a delicate, elegant linearity, a style which is still far from the intense pathos of his late work."<ref name="GCI"/>  The identity of his patron is unknown.{{sfn|Malaguzzi|Botticelli|2004|page=40}}

The interrelationship of light, shapes and voids confers an ethereal quality to the work.{{efn-ua|"The glimmer which pervades them seems to be unleashed by these figures and it spreads throughout the surrounding spaces. Besides the light, even the pyramid-like layout of the two sacred figures feeds the perception of an absolutely perfect moment."<ref name="milano"/>}} Indeed, the painting might be considered as newly rediscovered, as a recent restoration revealed a luminescent sky and bright morning aura, which had been obscured by layers of centuries-old varnish.<ref name="Backus">{{cite news |url=http://www.lagazzettadelmezzogiorno.it/GdM_traduci_notizia.php?IDNotizia=386348&IDCategotia= |title=Botticelli exhibit unveils surprises for art scholars: Show at Milan's Poldi Pezzoli museum gathers eight key works |first1=Emily |last1=Backus |newspaper=[[La Gazzetta del Mezzogiorno]] |location=Milan |date=30 November 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2014 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name="Onuchina">{{cite web |url=http://artinvestment.ru/en/news/exhibitions/20110104_boticelli_milan.html |title=Eight masterpieces by Botticelli in Milan |date=1 April 2011 |first1=Maria |last1=Onuchina |publisher=ARTinvestment.RU |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref> 
One is reminded of other Marian images made prior to the year 1470. Botticelli might have been influenced by [[Filippo Lippi]]'s ''Madonna and Child with an Angel'' from the [[Ospedale degli Innocenti|Hospital of the Innocents]] in Florence.<ref name="museupoldi"/> <!-- The painting has a rectangular shape, which is rare in the later production of Botticelli in the 1470s. -->

Botticelli and the ''Madonna of the Book'' were the subject of renewed interest in the 19th century. In its "extraordinary beauty" it appealed to Italians in particular who saw in it a source of national identity, during Italian unification ("[[Risorgimento]]").<ref name="Sidney">{{cite web |url=http://sydney.edu.au/news/84.html?newsstoryid=8813 |title=New light on Botticelli's beauty: Discoveries at the Poldi Pezzoli Museum, Milan |date=13 March 2012 |publisher=[[University of Sydney]] |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> Among Botticelli's admirers was [[Gian Giacomo Poldi Pezzoli]], who bequeathed his private collection and his apartment to the public.<ref name="Sidney"/>  Dr Annalisa Zanni, the Poldi Pezzoli Museum director, recently discovered more about Botticelli's technique and use of materials, as exemplified in the ''Madonna of the Book''. For example, she discovered that Botticelli's top layer of blue was [[lapis lazuli]], a "very precious and very expensive ingredient, indicating it was commissioned by a highly prestigious patron".<ref name="Backus"/><ref name="Onuchina"/><ref name="Sidney"/>

It is housed in the [[Museo Poldi Pezzoli]] in Milan, Italy.<ref name="museupoldi"/><ref name="milano">{{cite web |url=http://www.turismo.milano.it/wps/portal/?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=en/SITur/HOME/artecultura/capolavori/opere/opera26 |title=Madonna with Child (Madonna of the book)/ Casa Museo Poldi Pezzoli |work=Milan is Tourism |year=2010 |publisher=Milano City |accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref>{{efn-ua|A larger, more detailed copy is displayed at the [[Museum of Biblical Art (Dallas)]], Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biblicalarts.org/#!services |publisher= [[Museum of Biblical Art (Manhattan)|Museum of Biblical Art]] |title=Galleries and Exhibitions |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://agnesashe.wordpress.com/2013/09/19/the-sincerest-form-of-flattery-and-botticellis-madonna-of-the-book/ |first1=Agnes |last1=Ashe |title=The Sincerest Form of Flattery and Botticelli's 'Madonna of the Book' |date=September 19, 2013 |publisher=Agnes Ashe |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>}}

